==English==

===Etymology===
First attested in 1600. From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|abstēmius||abstaining from wine}}; from {{term|ab||lang=la}}, {{term|abs||from|lang=la}} + {{term/t|la|tēmus}}, root of {{term/t|la|tēmētum||[[intoxicating]] drink, mead, wine}}, akin to {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|dämlich||stupid, silly|lang=de}}, {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|þám||mugginess|lang=non}}, {{etyl|sga|-}} {{term|tám||death|lang=sga}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|ताम्यति||he becomes stunned, exhausted|tr=tāmyati|lang=sa}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/æbˈstiː.mɪ.əs/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈsti.mi.əs/|/əbˈsti.mi.əs/}}
* {{rhymes|iːmiəs}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# [[sparing|Sparing]] in diet; [[refraining]] from a free use of food and strong drinks; [[temperate]]; [[abstinent]]; [[sparing]] in the [[indulgence]] of the appetite or passions. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=9}}</ref>
#* Instances of longevity are chiefly among the '''abstemious''' - [[w:John Arbuthnot|John Arbuthnot]].
#* Under his special eye '''Abstemious''' I grew up and thrived amain. - [[w:John Milton|John Milton]]
#* '''1919''', [[w:William Somerset Maugham|W. Somerset Maugham]], ''[[w:The Moon and Sixpence|The Moon and Sixpence]]'', [[s:The Moon and Sixpence/Chapter XXVIII|chapter 28]]
#*: In the dimness of the landing I could not see him very well, but there was something in his voice that surprised me. I knew he was of '''abstemious''' habit or I should have thought he had been drinking.
# [[sparing|Sparingly]] used; used with [[temperance]] or [[moderation]]. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* an '''abstemious''' diet - [[w:Edward Gibbon|Edward Gibbon]]
# Marked by, or [[spent]] in, [[abstinence]]; as, an ''abstemious'' life.
#* One '''abstemious''' day. - [[w:Alexander Pope|Alexander Pope]]
# {{context|rare|lang=en}} [[promotive|Promotive]] of [[abstemiousness]].
#* Such is the virtue of the '''abstemious''' well. - [[w:John Dryden|John Dryden]]
